    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-05-23T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-05-23T16:00:00-05:00" n="103"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d103">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51W89 U.S.S.R./62: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_BWC1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bullitt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-05-24T00:00:00+03:00"
                            >May 24, 1934—midnight</date>.<lb/>[Received May 24—8:28
                        p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>104. Your 91, May 23, 4 p.m. I understand that it is the opinion of the Attorney
                    General that the type of credit offered by General Motors to the Soviet
                    Government is not forbidden by the Johnson bill therefore I cannot see how our
                    Government can forbid or discourage such a transaction. If we should warn
                    General Motors that <persName corresp="#p_LMM1">Litvinov</persName> had agreed
                    to pay extra interest on all such credits <persName corresp="#p_LMM1"
                        >Litvinov</persName> would deny the statement promptly and a public
                    controversy might result, the domestic political consequences of which I am in
                    no position to judge.</p>
                <p>I assume from paragraph 2 of your 91 that you desire me to make no further moves
                    but to await tranquilly further proposals by the Soviet Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWC1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bullitt</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
